                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-43-off194 t17511016-43-crimeloc196"></join>. The prisoner <rs id="t17511016-43-deflabel197" type="occupation">worked journey work</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-43-defend310 t17511016-43-deflabel197"></join> with me last July; he absconded on a Thursday night; when I went to do up the wigs on Saturday morning I missed two, one the property of Mr. 
               <persName id="t17511016-43-person317">
                  John 
                  Bedford 
               <interp inst="t17511016-43-person317" type="surname" value="Bedford"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-43-person317" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-43-person317" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , which cost him three guineas, and not the worse for ware. Mr. Tarris was offered a guinea and half for his but a little before, and would not take it.</p>
               <p>Q. When did you see the wigs last?</p>
               <p>Martin. They were in the shop just before he went away.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you owe the prisoner any thing?</p>
               <p>Martin. No, he was at work for me but that day.</p>
               <p>Q. Have you seen the wigs since?</p>
               <p>Martin. No, I have not; I took the prisoner up yesterday was se'nnight in Barnaby-street Sussex; he was at work there. I took him before Sir Samuel Gore, where he owned he took them out of my shop, and sold them in Rosemary-lane for two shillings.</p>
               <p>Q. What was the value of them, second hand.</p>
               <p>Martin. One was well worth two guineas, the other a guinea.</p>
               <p>
            
